<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Which GDP calculation method adds up all expenditures in the economy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Income approach</option>
            <option letter="b">Value-added approach</option>
            <option letter="c">Expenditure approach</option>
            <option letter="d">Production approach</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>The expenditure approach calculates GDP by summing C (consumption) + I (investment) + G (government spending) + (X-M) (net exports), measuring total spending on final goods and services.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Which is NOT counted in GDP calculations?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">A new car purchased from a dealer</option>
            <option letter="b">Used car sold between private individuals</option>
            <option letter="c">Government purchase of military equipment</option>
            <option letter="d">Construction of a new house</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Used goods sold between private individuals are not counted in GDP because they were already counted when first produced. Only new goods and services produced in the current year are included in GDP.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What happens to cyclical unemployment during a recession?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It decreases as structural unemployment increases</option>
            <option letter="b">It increases as aggregate demand falls</option>
            <option letter="c">It remains constant at the natural rate</option>
            <option letter="d">It disappears completely</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>During a recession, falling aggregate demand leads to decreased production and higher cyclical unemployment as businesses lay off workers due to reduced economic activity.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What distinguishes the CPI from the GDP deflator?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">CPI only includes consumer goods while GDP deflator includes all goods produced</option>
            <option letter="b">CPI measures inflation while GDP deflator measures output</option>
            <option letter="c">CPI uses current year quantities while GDP deflator uses base year quantities</option>
            <option letter="d">CPI is always higher than the GDP deflator</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The CPI measures price changes in a fixed basket of consumer goods and services, while the GDP deflator measures price changes in all goods and services produced in the economy, including capital goods and government services.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
